Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – The invasion of Ukraine by Russia on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of China's Spring Festival celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully drafted, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin free rein to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider his confirmation as China's leader for life later this year a mere formality.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario according to which he will rise to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin embarked on realizing his lifelong dream with incredible brutality.
Approaching his 70th birthday, Putin believes that if he wants to imprint his mark on Russian history, now or never is the time.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need a tsar they can blindly follow.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of the Russian people, emotionally sensitive to the core.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were ready to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I established a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989 just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have observed his rise to power very closely, being conscious of his cruelty.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to ruins. And he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a skilled KGB operator, but he seems to have changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be in exactly the same position as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have put up an incredibly brave resistance against an opponent that nothing seems able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was mistaken.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 'Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a deep anger.
But the Russian army performed poorly when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers.
The deep-seated corruption in defense contract allocation also played a significant role in his inadequate results.
Yet, instead of blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally lost his mind.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and appears to be acting without facing any resistance.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and ignores all rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been hit and the electrical network supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In besieged Marioupol, 400,000 people went without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia might well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive arms to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to buy Russian-made MiG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots can operate.
This could make all the difference.
No matter the outcome, Putin has already accomplished something remarkable by reinforcing the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, it seems that Xi has realized that Putin is acting alone.
On March 8, one day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remain "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say that he supported their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
